isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.56) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.25. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.26, p < .001, 95% CI [13.02, 14.04]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.37, p = 0.716, 95% CI [-0.86, 0.59]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -3.04, S.E. = 0.40, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.82, -2.25]; Std. beta = -0.75, 95% CI [-0.94, -0.56])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -2.04, S.E. = 3.04, p = 0.501, 95% CI [-8.00, 3.91]; Std. beta = -0.50, 95% CI [-1.97, 0.96])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.47, S.E. = 0.59, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.62, -1.31]; Std. beta = -0.61, 95% CI [-0.89, -0.32])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -4.07, S.E. = 3.51, p = 0.246, 95% CI [-10.95, 2.81]; Std. beta = -1.00, 95% CI [-2.70, 0.69])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
